This example demonstrates a "6PE-lite" deployment: two IPv6-addressed edge
islands connected across a small, purely IPv4-addressed, IPv4-signaled
SR-MPLS (RFC 8660) core, using the same signaling-free node-SID label
programming and ~SrPolicy ingress steering as examples/mpls/sr/ -- see that
example's README first for the SR-MPLS basics this one builds on.

Topology
--------

Four ~SrMplsRouter nodes form a small chain plus one chord: R1-R2-R3-R4 (all
metric 1), plus a direct R1-R3 link that shortcuts across the middle hop.
hostA hangs off R1; hostB and hostC hang off R4 -- two IPv6 "customers"
reachable through the same egress router, each steered there a different
way (mirroring examples/mpls/sr/'s first two flows, at a smaller scale and
carrying IPv6 instead of IPv4).

R1 and R4 are the only routers with an extra IPv6-addressed interface (one
each, toward their local island); their OTHER (core-facing) interfaces, and
BOTH of R2's and R3's interfaces, are plain IPv4 -- exactly the P/PE split a
real 6PE deployment has (only the edge routers need any IPv6 awareness at
all). Router IDs are 1.1.1.1..4.4.4.4; node SIDs are 1..4 (R1=1, ..., R4=4);
with the default srgbBase (16000), R4's node-SID label is 16004.

Only R1 carries an ~SrPolicy policy table (policies.xml), with two entries,
one per destination host:

1. hostA -> hostB, ``segments="node:4"`` (unconstrained node-SID policy)

   Names only the destination's node SID; the path taken is whatever
   ~SegmentRouting's own shortest-path computation over the network picks.
   Here, that is the R1-R3 chord: a 2-hop shortcut (cost 2) that beats the
   R1-R2-R3-R4 chain (cost 3). R1 (ingress) PUSHes and forwards directly to
   R3 over the chord; R3, being R4's direct neighbor, POPs (penultimate-hop-
   popping, RFC 8660 Section 2) and forwards on to R4, which delivers to
   hostB via ordinary L3 routing. R2 never sees this flow at all.

2. hostA -> hostC, ``segments="node:2 node:4"`` (explicit-path policy)

   Names R2's node SID as an intermediate waypoint before the real
   destination's node SID, forcing the longer 3-hop chain route
   (R1-R2-R3-R4) and avoiding the chord entirely -- SR traffic engineering
   without any signaling protocol. R2 genuinely transits (SWAP), then R3
   POPs (PHP is still what happens at the LAST hop before R4, regardless of
   which path got the packet there). Both flows therefore end with the same
   PHP-at-R3 step; what differs is whether R2 is on the path at all.

Both flows are simple periodic UDP flows (128-byte datagrams every 10 ms),
started 0.1s apart; sim-time-limit is 10s.

Making PHP carry IPv6 correctly: the inner explicit-null label
----------------------------------------------------------------

A node-SID label is shared by ALL traffic destined to that node, of either
address family -- unlike a FEC-keyed LIB entry (static XML, LDP, RSVP-TE),
where one entry corresponds to exactly one FEC of exactly one family, a
node-SID's PHP POP entry is installed ONCE per node, family-agnostic, by
~SegmentRouting. R2 and R3 above are given no IPv6 configuration whatsoever,
yet R3 still correctly decapsulates hostA's IPv6 traffic without
misinterpreting it as IPv4 -- this works because ~SrPolicy pushes an EXTRA,
innermost label under the node-SID label whenever a matched policy's
destination is IPv6: RFC 3032's IPv6 Explicit NULL label (value 2). It rides
underneath the node-SID label(s) through every transit PHP pop untouched (a
non-bottom-of-stack pop never stamps a payload protocol -- see
~Mpls::popLabel()), and is only actually processed once it reaches the
bottom of the stack, at the true egress (R4), where ~Mpls's existing
explicit-null handling (built for Workstream F3 Phase 2, exercised here for
the first time) pops it and stamps the packet IPv6 -- regardless of what
R3's own (also family-agnostic) node-SID LIB entry would have defaulted to.
Look for ``doStackOps: {PUSH 2; PUSH 16004}`` at R1, a plain ``{POP}`` at R3
(popping only the node-SID label, label 2 still underneath), and "IPv6
explicit null label, popping and delivering to L3" at R4.

How to observe it
------------------

Run with Cmdenv and an "info" log level (the default in this ini) and grep
the output for ``doStackOps:`` lines. Per-router counts over the whole run
(confirmed by actually running this example): R1 pushes for BOTH flows; R2
only ever appears for the explicit-path flow (hostA->hostC) -- the
unconstrained flow (hostA->hostB) never touches it; R3 POPs the node-SID
label for both flows (it is the PHP router for R4 on both the chord and the
chain paths). ``hostB``'s and ``hostC``'s ``packetReceived:count`` scalars
confirm actual end-to-end IPv6 delivery through the SR-MPLS core.

What this models vs. real 6PE
------------------------------

This is deliberately "6PE-lite", not a real 6PE (RFC 4798) control plane:

- **No BGP labeled-unicast.** Real 6PE distributes IPv6 reachability AND a
  per-prefix label via MP-BGP (IPv6 AFI/SAFI, "BGP-LU"); a full BGP-LU/6VPE
  control plane is its own, much larger modeling effort (out of scope for
  this workstream -- see the plan's "explicitly out of scope" section).
  Here, R1's edge-to-edge IPv6-prefix-to-label mapping is static/SR-policy
  configuration (policies.xml) -- the same simplification this codebase
  already makes for IGP/SID advertisement (see examples/mpls/sr/README and
  the users guide's SR-MPLS section: no OSPF-SR/IS-IS-SR flooding is
  modeled either, the sidTable is static, network-wide configuration).
- **No per-(prefix,family) label.** Real 6PE's BGP label is allocated per
  advertised IPv6 prefix, so PE routers never need a demultiplexing trick --
  the label itself already says "this is the IPv6 route to 2001:db8:20::/64".
  This model's SR node-SID is allocated per ROUTER, shared by both address
  families, so it needs the inner explicit-null label described above to
  tell the egress which family is underneath. That is a data-plane
  workaround for the underlying scheme's coarser granularity, not something
  a real 6PE deployment needs to do.
- **No IPv6 route redistribution.** hostB's and hostC's prefixes are
  reachable from R1 purely because policies.xml says so; nothing floods or
  redistributes IPv6 reachability between routers the way BGP would in a
  real deployment.

Simplifications inherited from examples/mpls/sr/
--------------------------------------------------

As documented there: the SID table is static, network-wide configuration
(no OSPF-SR/IS-IS-SR flooding); the SRGB is homogeneous across all routers;
there is no protection/fast-reroute (a link or node failure reroutes
node-SID traffic via ~Ted's own shortest-path recomputation, once ~Ted
itself notices the failure).
